          "title": "Citizenship in heaven and the awaited transformation (3:20-21)",
          "body": "The chapter climaxes in eschatological hope. *Politeuma* (3:20) — a noun unique in the NT — names the heavenly commonwealth to which the Philippians belong. Philippi was a Roman colony whose residents held Roman citizenship though they lived in Macedonia; Paul transposes the image. The believer's true civic identity is in heaven, *from which* (*ex hou*) we await a Savior. The verb *apekdechometha* (we eagerly await) is the New Testament's intensified term for expectant longing (cf. Romans 8:23). What He will do at His coming is named precisely (3:21): *metaschēmatisei* (will transform) the body of *tapeinōsis* (humble state) *symmorphon* (conformed to) the body of His glory. The chapter that began with renouncing fleshly confidence ends with the promise that the very flesh once renounced will be glorified — not by human attainment but by the exertion of His power."
